Financial News Sentiment Prediction using Deep Learning & BERT
1. Introduction

Financial markets are heavily influenced by public sentiment expressed through news and social media platforms. Investors and analysts often rely on these signals to understand market trends and potential price movements. Sentiment analysis helps in automatically identifying whether a piece of financial news reflects positive, negative, or neutral sentiment.

The objective of this project is to build a sentiment classification system that categorizes financial tweets into Bearish, Bullish, or Neutral sentiments. Two approaches were implemented: a baseline LSTM-based deep learning model and a transformer-based FinBERT model. The performance of both models was compared to analyze the improvement achieved using transformer architectures.

2. Dataset

The dataset used in this project is the Twitter Financial News Sentiment dataset available on Hugging Face.

Key properties of the dataset:

Total samples: 11,932 financial tweets

Training set: 9,938 tweets

Validation set: 2,486 tweets

Language: English

Sentiment classes:

Label	Sentiment
0	Bearish
1	Bullish
2	Neutral

Each record contains a financial tweet and its corresponding sentiment label.

Example tweet:
$AAPL stock surges after strong quarterly earnings report

3. Data Preprocessing

Before training the models, several preprocessing steps were applied:

Text Cleaning

Removed URLs

Removed mentions (@user)

Removed hashtags

Removed extra spaces

Tokenization

LSTM model used Keras Tokenizer

FinBERT used WordPiece tokenizer

Sequence Padding

Tweets were padded to a fixed length of 50 tokens.

Dataset Preparation

Converted text sequences into numerical representations.

Prepared training and validation datasets.

4. Model Architecture
4.1 LSTM Baseline Model

The first model implemented was a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) neural network.

Architecture:
Embedding Layer
      ↓
LSTM Layer
      ↓
Dropout Layer
      ↓
Fully Connected Layer
      ↓
Softmax Output (3 classes)

Training configuration:

Optimizer: Adam

Learning rate: 0.001

Loss function: CrossEntropyLoss

Epochs: 5

The LSTM model serves as the baseline for comparison.
4.2 FinBERT Model

The second model used FinBERT, a transformer model specifically trained on financial text.

FinBERT is based on the BERT architecture, which uses self-attention mechanisms to understand contextual relationships between words in a sentence.

Advantages of FinBERT:

Pretrained on financial language

Captures contextual meaning

Handles complex financial terminology

Training configuration:

Model: ProsusAI/FinBERT

Optimizer: AdamW

Learning rate: 2e-5

Epochs: 3

Batch size: 16

5. Model Evaluation

The models were evaluated using the following metrics:

Accuracy

Macro F1-score

Precision and Recall

Confusion Matrix

Performance Comparison
Model	Accuracy	Macro F1
LSTM	~0.75	~0.74
FinBERT	~0.89	~0.88

The FinBERT model significantly outperformed the LSTM model due to its ability to capture contextual relationships using transformer attention mechanisms.

6. Deployment

To demonstrate real-time prediction, a Streamlit web application was developed.

The application allows users to:

Enter a financial news headline or tweet

Predict sentiment instantly

Display prediction confidence

Visualize probability distribution using charts

Example prediction:
Input: Tesla shares fall sharply after weak delivery numbers
Output: Bearish (88.2% confidence)

This makes the model accessible through a simple user interface.

7. Conclusion

This project demonstrated how natural language processing techniques can be applied to financial sentiment analysis. Two models were implemented and compared: an LSTM-based deep learning model and a transformer-based FinBERT model.

The results show that FinBERT significantly improves performance compared to traditional RNN-based models, achieving higher accuracy and better sentiment classification.

Future improvements could include:

Incorporating larger financial datasets

Using real-time financial news APIs

Building a full sentiment dashboard for market monitoring.